WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:03.604
If you were to borrow money
for different amounts of time,

00:00:03.604 --> 00:00:05.270
you could imagine the
person lending you

00:00:05.270 --> 00:00:07.780
the money might charge you
a different annual interest

00:00:07.780 --> 00:00:10.840
rate depending on the
perceived risk of having

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:13.310
the money out there for
that amount of time.

00:00:13.310 --> 00:00:15.430
And the same thing is true
when people lend money

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:17.120
to the federal government.

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:19.672
So when you think about US
treasuries, and US treasuries

00:00:19.672 --> 00:00:20.880
that have different maturity.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:24.050
And maturity just means when is
the government going to pay you

00:00:24.050 --> 00:00:26.430
back, you could imagine that
there are different interest

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:27.970
rates, or there's
different yields

00:00:27.970 --> 00:00:30.390
to maturity on that debt.

00:00:30.390 --> 00:00:32.371
So if we were to plot
it-- so let's say that,

00:00:32.371 --> 00:00:33.870
and I'm just going
to simplify here.

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:35.370
Let's say that
there's some treasury

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:37.709
debt that's maturing
in one month.

00:00:37.709 --> 00:00:39.250
And if you look at
the price that you

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:42.900
would have to pay for that
debt versus the amount of money

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:46.190
that the treasury is going
to pay you when it matures,

00:00:46.190 --> 00:00:50.070
you see that the yield there
is, let's say it is 1%.

00:00:50.070 --> 00:00:52.770
Let's say for treasuries
that are maturing

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:59.210
in three months
the yield is 1.5%.

00:00:59.210 --> 00:01:02.140
Let's say the treasuries
that are maturing in,

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:04.340
I'll just pick some
maturity dates here,

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:08.530
let's say in one
year the yield is 3%.

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:12.050
Let's do a couple more.

00:01:12.050 --> 00:01:17.620
Let's say in 10 years-- you're
essentially lending money

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:20.370
to the treasury for 10 years
now-- the annual interest

00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:22.900
rate on that, let's
say it's, I don't know,

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:25.520
let's say it's 3.5%.

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:27.410
And let's throw
one more up here.

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:30.820
Let's say if you were to lend
money to the US government

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:36.150
for 30 years the yield is
running at, let's say it's 4%.

00:01:36.150 --> 00:01:38.760
So here we have different
yields for different maturities.

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.870
And if we essentially
plot this on a graph,

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:43.164
we get ourselves a yield curve.

00:01:43.164 --> 00:01:44.830
And it's usually
called The Yield Curve.

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:46.550
When people talk
about The Yield Curve

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:49.610
they're talking about the
plot for the US Treasury

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:52.276
in dollars, US Treasury
bills and bonds.

00:01:52.276 --> 00:01:53.650
You can have a
yield curve really

00:01:53.650 --> 00:01:57.880
for any debt instrument, for
any corporate bonds, or even

00:01:57.880 --> 00:01:59.870
government securities
or corporate securities

00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:00.945
of other countries.

00:02:00.945 --> 00:02:03.070
But in general, when they
talk but The Yield Curve,

00:02:03.070 --> 00:02:05.390
they're talking
about US treasuries.

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:08.580
So let me draw a yield
curve right over here.

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:11.030
So on this axis I
will put maturity.

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:15.627
Let me scroll down a
little bit, so maturity.

00:02:15.627 --> 00:02:17.460
And we have a bunch of
different maturities.

00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:18.750
We have one month.

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:20.550
Let's squeeze it, one month.

00:02:20.550 --> 00:02:22.099
We have three months.

00:02:22.099 --> 00:02:23.640
And this will be
completely to scale.

